Introduction to ggplot2

ggplot2

ggplot2 is a library in R used to visualize and plot data, included in the tidyverse package.

  • ggplot2 implements the grammar of graphics which is a system for describing and building graphs.

  • allows you to build graphics with a lot of freedom and is easy to learn the grammar

  • avoids common pitfalls through lack of functionality or warning messages:
    • 3D Graphics
    • Pie Charts
    • Dual axes
    • long/overlapping labels

Components of the Layered Grammar

  • data and aesthetic mappings
  • geometric objects
  • scales
  • statistics and transformations
  • a coordinate system
  • facet specification
  • themes

The data, mappings, statistical transformation, and geometric object form a layer. A plot can have multiple layers when such as when we overlay a scatter plot with a smoothed line

scales map values from the data to aesthetics of the data, such as: colour, size or shape, the legend, or an axis.

coordinate systems are how the data is mapped to the plot on the screen. By default this is usually Cartesian coordinate system but polar coordinates and map projections can also be used.

faceting is used to generate many of the same types of plots based on categories of your data. Also known as latticing/trellising.

themes are the actual visuals of the plot, not linked to data. Axis labels, rotation of labels, colour, font, grid lines, etc.

Layer:geoms

A layer combines data, aesthetic mapping, a geom_, a stat and position argument. There are many types of geoms_ and each have a unique specification and requirements.

and many more.

Within a geom_ is also statistics, each geom_ has a default statistic.

ggplot2

To call a plot in r we start with ggplot() Then we need to supply the data we are mapping to the plot. ggplot(data=mpg).

aes() is the aesthetic mappings ggplot(data=mt_cars, aes())

Then we can add objects and layers with a + and the type of layer geom_

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

Examples

Using the mpg data frame in ggplot2.

manufacturer model displ year cyl trans drv cty hwy fl class
audi a4 1.8 1999 4 auto(l5) f 18 29 p compact
audi a4 1.8 1999 4 manual(m5) f 21 29 p compact
audi a4 2.0 2008 4 manual(m6) f 20 31 p compact
audi a4 2.0 2008 4 auto(av) f 21 30 p compact
audi a4 2.8 1999 6 auto(l5) f 16 26 p compact
audi a4 2.8 1999 6 manual(m5) f 18 26 p compact

Among the variables in mpg are:

  1. displ, a cars engine size, in litres.

  2. hwy, a cars fuel efficiency on the highway, in miles per gallon (mpg). A car with a low fuel efficiency consumes more fuel than a car with a high fuel efficiency when they travel the same distance.

Plotting

Do cars with big engines use more fuel than cars with small engines?

Recall that:

  1. We need to supply the data to the plot. This is mpg.

  2. aes() is the aesthetic mappings we are mapping hwy and displ

  3. The geom_point is used to create scatterplots.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

The x and y arguments of aes() specify which variables to map to the x and y axes. ggplot2 looks for these variables in the data argument (mpg).

We can also write:

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy))+
  geom_point()

This is because ggplot() is globally defined so any geom_ preceding it can inherit what is inside of the ggplot parentheses.

You can also define data in the geom_

ggplot()+
  geom_point(data=mpg,aes(x=displ,y=hwy))

Assign ggplot() as a variable

Assigning a plot to a variable allows you to interact with, and add to the plot.

plot <- ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy))
plot + 
  geom_point()

The convention we will use for this workshop is:

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy))+
  geom_point()

Aesthetics

  • Add colour to aes() further examine relationships from a variable within the data
  • Add colour outside of aes() to define one colour for the data contained in the geom_
ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy,colour=class))+
  geom_point()

Outside aes

A common error in ggplot2 is putting colour or fill in the wrong place. Class is contained within mpg, so if we want to map the aesthetics to the data it needs to be within the brackets. Otherwise, outside the brackets ggplot does not know how to interpret this :

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy),colour=class)+
  geom_point()

Alternatively, if we want everything to be one colour we can define the colour outside of aes or within our geom_

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy))+
    geom_point(color="darkblue")

*Note adding color="darkblue" to the global ggplot2 will not work

Size

The size of the plot objects can also be changed to scale with their values. Also known as a bubble chart

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy,size=cyl))+
    geom_point()

Alter transparency by adding an alpha parameter to geom_point(). Alpha ranges from 0-1. Adding alpha adds to ggplot() adds a legend that we dont want

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy,size=cyl,alpha=0.8))+
    geom_point()

So we add the aesthetic to geom_point

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy,size=cyl))+
    geom_point(alpha=0.8)

Alternatively

ggplot(data=mpg)+
    geom_point(aes(x=displ,y=hwy,size=cyl),alpha=0.8)

Conditions

ggplot can use colours and conditions to output into your plot. Assign colours based on the values of cyl that are greater than 7

ggplot(data=mpg,aes(x=displ,y=hwy,colour=cyl > 7))+
    geom_point(alpha=0.8)

Shape

Recall the types of available shapes: 

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy,shape=class))+
    geom_point()
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because
## more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7. Consider
## specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Notice that we get a warning here, ggplot2 will only plot a maximum of 6 different shapes by default.

ggplot2 has built in data visualization principles.

Shape

To assign one shape to all the points we assign it to the geom

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy))+
    geom_point(shape=3)

Bar Charts

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=class))+
    geom_bar()

geom_bar() uses stat_count() by default. If we pre-computed our data and already have the total count then we specify identity.

mpg %>%
  group_by(class)%>%
  count()
## # A tibble: 7 x 2
## # Groups:   class [7]
##   class          n
##   <chr>      <int>
## 1 2seater        5
## 2 compact       47
## 3 midsize       41
## 4 minivan       11
## 5 pickup        33
## 6 subcompact    35
## 7 suv           62
mpg %>%
  group_by(class)%>%
  count()%>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_bar(aes(x=class,y=n), stat = "identity")

Stacking Layers

ggplot(data=mpg, aes(x=displ,y=hwy))+
    geom_point(shape=3)+
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Scales

Change the color scale using the discrete viridis scale

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(aes(x= displ,y=hwy, colour=class))+
  scale_color_viridis_d()

Change the scale of the x and y axis

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(aes(x= displ,y=hwy, colour=class))+
  scale_color_viridis_d()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(2,4,6)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(10,45))

Within the scales, we can specify the breaks on the x-axis to label. On the y-axis limits sets the minimum value to 10 and maximum to 45.

Since our y scale is continuous we can alter the breaks using scale_y_continuous. seq is starting a sequence at 5, going to 45 and increasing by an interval of 5. Our breaks should occur at 5, 5+5 = 10, 10+5=15etc

Themes

Themes

Labels

labs can specify the axis labels, title, caption, fill, colour and shape labels

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(aes(x= displ,y=hwy, colour=class))+
  scale_color_viridis_d()+
   scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(5, 45, by = 5))+
  labs(x="Engine Displacement (L)",y="Highway Miles per gallon", colour="Type of Car",
       title="Fuel Economy of Popular Cars", subtitle = "From 1999 to 2008",
       caption="Source: Environmental Protection Agency")

Preset Themes

There are a few preset themes in R

Theme_bw

p + theme_bw()

Theme_classic

p+ theme_classic()

Theme_dark

p+ theme_dark()

Theme_light

p+ theme_light()

Theme_void

p+ theme_void()

Saving

There are a lot of ways to save a plot ggsave() will save the most recent plot. In R Markdown, we have already specified all figures will be saved in the Figs directory by their chunk name.
